If we read the ablative, it will have an active meaning, as Virg. G. 4. 468 ‘ caligantem nigra formidine silvam! This is Horace's use of the adjective in Od. 2. 17. 18. If we have the nominative, it will have a passive sense, ‘timorous‚' as in Ter. Eun. 4. 6. 18, etc. In either case its force seems to lie, as the Scholiast implies, in its suggestion of the ‘awfulness’ of night, ‘ now that your spell is on the woods and their inhabitants.' The two verses combine the ideas of the hour of midnight 'as the time when magic powers are strongest, and of the lover awake when all the rest of the world is asleep, as Dido in Virg. 57—60. The prayer of the next four lines is not quite clear. Why does she wish the dogs to bark? As a sign that the scented old fop is coming to her door? or to frighten him from the doors of her rivals as he comes through the Subura? The first view would be illustrated by the sign of Daphnis' approach in answer to the spells in Virgil's Phar- maceutria, E. 8. 107 ⁴ Hylax in limine latrat? The second, however, gives a better explanation of ‘quod omnes rideant‚' and of the care with which she has herself prepared the perfumed unguent, which he uses in his vanity without guessing its purpose. She is meant to make him (and herself thereby) ridiculous to the reader; but she would not wish him to be laughed at, except as a means of keeping him to herself.

58. Suburanae. ‘Subura' was the broad hollow formed by the junction of the valleys between the Quirinal, Viminal‚ and Esquiline hills, and opening on the Fora. It was a busy part of Rome, but has a bad name in the poets ; Prop. 4. 7. 15, Mart. 6. 66, Juv. 3. 5.
